<dl id="s17027v"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17027v">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s17all.htm#s17027v">sector 27(v)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> fire into sky frighten eclipse dragon,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In all times and among all people we find traces of popular superstitions connected with <mark>eclipses</mark>. Here, the abnormal absence of the Moon&apos;s light is regarded as a sign of divine anger: the humble penitents betake themselves to prayer to ward off the divine anger. There, the cruelty of the dread <mark>dragon</mark> is to be averted: he <mark>must be chased away by cries and threats, and the sky is bombarded with shots</mark> to deliver the victim from his monstrous oppressor. <small> Camille Flammarion, <a name="CFAA" href="/udra/udex.htm#CFAA"><cite title="source">Astronomy for Amateurs</cite></a> (1904), 267f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
